<TEXT>
salim shaar always liked 
fixing things he spent the last afternoon of his life laying new 
tiles on the family porch and wiring new lights 
he planned to finish the job the next day after a morning of 
throwing stones at israeli soldiers but a soldier thought he saw a 
firebomb in salims hand and the next time salim crossed the porch 
he was carried with a bullet hole in his head 
on an afternoon two weeks later members of the family sat at 
home sipping strong arab coffee and talking about the shy 
23yearold electrician bethlehems first martyr of the arab 
rebellion that began nearly five months ago in the israelioccupied 
lands 
this uprising changes everyone said salims father khalil 
it turns a sane man into a crazy man it turns a shy man into an 
angry man 
the clearest evidence of the change in salim is in his diary a 
frayed notepad from a souvenir shop lovingly preserved by his 
family it speaks of his growing desperation 
i dont dream about toys anymore mother salim wrote in an 
entry directed to his mother fatmah several weeks before his 
death when they killed my friends i grew up a thousand years 
when the violence began dec 8 salim was a goodnatured young 
man devoted to his job who often stopped at the homes of neighbors 
after work to see if anything needed fixing his family says 
people appreciated him and his work made him happy said 
his brother mohammed 21 he didnt have any great ambitions 
salim was happy at his familys home and had added a room to it 
where he could settle one day with a wife he filled the new 
closets with books on electricity and moved into the room only 
weeks before he died 
his possessions do not seem those of a man driven to die for a 
cause they reveal instead a young man who liked music turkish 
singers and traditional arab tunes and was an amateur 
photographer who filling albums with pictures of his friends 
friends and family said salim began to change when the 
intefadah arabic for uprising came to the towns and refugee 
camps near bethlehem taking the lives of young palestinians like 
himself 
salim was affected by what was going on said a cousin 
mussa he had many friends who went to prison and it became 
obvious to him that one day he too would go to jail so he wanted 
to prepare himself 
he began spending free time at the nearby dheishe refugee camp 
talking to palestinians who had been in jail and visiting the 
families of prisoners to offer emotional support 
in the diary salim sounds alternately desperate and defiant 
whats a human being worth without a homeland without a flag 
without an address he wrote and later the enemy planes can 
raid our camps and kill our children but cannot kill our will to 
fight 
the entry for friday april 1 the night before his death was 
the most striking if my friends come back without me mother 
dont cry every tear in your eyes is oil to light a lamp of 
freedom 
salim was in a good mood that saturday morning his family said 
he took a shower donned khaki trousers and a sweater kissed his 
mother and said if i come back i wont be late 
he and his brother mohammed set off to join friends in 
bethlehems market gathering stones along the way they became 
part of a group in central manger square where israeli soldiers 
were stationed 
when its over you go back home ill go to a friends 
house salim told mohammed anticipating the housetohouse 
search that often followed protests 
according to the army account of the mornings events a soldier 
thought he saw a firebomb in salims hand but the family called 
that absurd what noone disputes is that salim was killed 
instantly by a bullet that went through his right cheek and out the 
back of his neck 
his parents still in mourning clothes two weeks later became 
defiant in their grief when asked if they would stop their seven 
other children from joining protests 
we all have the right to demonstrate for what we believe in 
fatmah said i will never take that from my children 
khalil nodded and added besides salim is not really dead he 
lives on as a hero for our town 
</TEXT>
