<TEXT>
the writer a photographer for the associated 
press in managua accompanied the contra rebels for two days here 
is his account 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
commander halcon and his band of 
nicaraguan rebels move freely around what they call their 
liberated zone in the jungles near the caribbean coast 
they are willing to talk peace but wont lay down their arms 
we have received orders from our high command to stop 
shooting halcon said as he sat under a tree while his men rested 
nearby but we are not dropping our guard the enemy cannot be 
trusted 
a peasant widow provided food and coffee to his company of young 
rebels including several women 
halcon a former sandinista who fought against the national 
guard of late strongman president anastasio somoza and his troops 
are in the jungles of southern zelaya province near the caribbean 
coast 
they are part of the southern front of the democratic nicarguan 
force or fdn the main contra force which has fought to overthrow 
the sandinista government 
the area is one of seven set up under a 60day ceasefire 
agreement between the usbacked contras and the sandinista 
under the agreement the sandinistas have promised not to attack 
contra troops congregating in the areas 
they dont come here anyway halcon said we liberated 
this zone a long time ago 
looking around at his troops halcon said there is no one 
here among us against his will 
the people know we are not mercenaries he said 
journalists traveled with the group for a day visiting 
different camps where they met groups of rebels halcon said he 
commands three companies of 100 men each in the rugged eastern zone 
sandinista army troops evacuated many of the residents from the 
mountainous region two years ago in an effort to remove the rebels 
social base but some people refused to leave 
they often help the contras and provide food they do the same 
for the sandinista army when it moves in 
some cattle still roam the area and contra groups use abandoned 
farms 
halcon and his men appeared to be wellarmed and in good 
spirits they had enough medicine and beef and plenty of usmade 
candy to eat at night they danced to tapes of mexican ranchera 
music then slept in hammocks made of silky parachute cloth 
the commander said the last air drop of us supplies to the 
group came a month ago 
under the ceasefire that took effect april 1 rebels may 
receive humanitarian aid through neutral international 
organizations once they are settled in the designated zones 
details of the truce are still being worked out in talks which 
will resume thursday 
halcon said he had received two letters from the regional 
commander of the sandinista army asking him to meet with the 
government represntatives in an effort to achieve peace 
he said he was waiting for further instructions from contra 
headquarters there have already been several meetings of army and 
rebel groups on the field since the ceasefire went into effect 
we will do whatever our leaders tell us halcon said if 
we had a complete ceasefire it would be the most beautiful thing 
we have been fighting among nicaraguans for too long but we are 
armed campesinos and we are willing to fight and we are not 
going to lay down our arms unless there is a definitive 
ceasefire 
we will lay down our arms when the sandinistas lay down 
theirs when there is a democratic government in nicaragua 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

