<TEXT>
the european economic community needs to get 
serious about seeking solutions to an increasingly chaotic 
condition in global agricultural trade says agriculture 
secretary richard e lyng 
but the eec is unwilling to even define a longterm goal in the 
reform of the rules of international trade lyng said they 
term our proposal to eventually eliminate tradedistorting 
subsidies as unrealistic or too far too fast yet they have 
not stated what alternative they will accept 
it has been almost a year and a half since the new uruguay round 
of multinational trade talks began under the general agreement on 
tariffs and trade or gatt yet lyng said the major agricultural 
shippers are expanding export subsidies rather than reducing them 
lyng warned that failure to make progress in the negotiations by 
the time of the gatt midterm review in montreal next december 
will bring into question the chance for eventual success of the 
uruguay round 
im not pessimistic but ill have to admit theres not a 
whole lot to be optimistic about at this point lyng said 
lyng said the eec for example has just paid a subsidy equal to 
126 per metric ton to wheat exporters and continues to pay huge 
subsidies on a host of other commodities including mixed feed 
291 per ton durum wheat 281 per ton and barley 130 per ton 
the united states he said at a meeting of the newspaper farm 
editors of america is calling for agricultural trade reform at the 
uruguay round ultimately under the us proposal international 
trade barriers and subsidies would be eliminated over a period of 
10 years or so 
lyng said the excessive influence of governments in farm 
product markets leads to a grossly inefficient allocation of 
resources in developed countries and leave poorer developing 
countries in economic shambles 
the worst offenders are the big nations who are unwilling or 
reluctant to change he said japan with huge trade surpluses 
from exports of industrial and consumer goods clings to import 
barriers on products such as beef rice and citrus 
other exporting countries including the eec say they are not 
alone in subsidizing agricultural trade and point to the export 
enhancement program operated by the us department of agriculture 
under eep as it is known private exporters are given surplus 
usdaowned commodities so they can sell grain or other products to 
selected foreign countries including the soviet union china and 
others department officials claim eep was necessary to compete 
with europes subsidized exports 
after lyng spoke to the farm editors his department routinely 
announced several more export subsidy actions under the program 
china was sold an additional 95000 tons of us wheat which 
carried subsidies of 2752 per ton 
another eep subsidy was for 300 tons of frozen broiler chickens 
or fryer legs sold to the canary islands the subsidies amounted to 
about 237 per ton officials said an additional 400 tons of frozen 
poultry are still available for sale to the canary islands at 
subsidized prices 
