<TEXT>
house action has taken the united states on 
its way to becoming a full participant in international agreements 
aimed at preventing genocide 
by a voice vote the house on monday approved largely symbolic 
legislation setting stiff penalties for the crime of genocide the 
legislation which is backed by the reagan administration must 
also be ratified by the senate 
although the international convention on the prevention and 
punishment of the crime of genocide was adopted by the united 
nations general assembly and signed by the united states in 1948 
it was not ratified by the senate until 1986 
the international accords are aimed at preventing and punishing 
attempts to destroy in whole or in major part a national ethnic 
religious racial or religious group 
since the convention itself contains no mechanism to punish 
violators the nations which have signed and ratified it it are 
required to pass antigenocide laws 
reagan administration officials contend that full implementation 
of us participation in the genocide convention will remove an 
international human rights embarrassment 
a report on the bill issued by the house judiciary committee 
quoted assistant secretary of state richard schifter on the us 
position 
most of us will agree that genocide is not likely to take 
place within the borders of the united states schifter said 
our action on this convention is above all a symbolic act 
it underlines our role of leadership in the free world on 
behalf of the cause of human rights 
the bill sets prison sentences ranging from 20 years to life for 
people convicted of such offenses and sets fines of up to 1 
milliion 
it also provides for a prison term of up to five years and a 
fine of up to 500000 for people convicted of inciting others to 
undertake acts of genocide 
those penalties would apply to crimes of genocide committed by 
us nationals or which are committed within the united states 
the legislation also suspends the statute of limitations for 
prosecutions on allegations of genocide 
