a high court judge ruled that the bones of a 10th 
century english king can be transferred to a russian exiles church 
near london 
deputy judge robert wright decided monday that the fragmented 
1000yearold bones of the young saxon monarch edward the martyr 
can be moved to the russian orthodox church community at brookwood 
the bones are now in a box in a bank vault and the judge said 
they can be transferred when the church converted from an anglican 
cemetery chapel has been officially approved as a secure place 
its an answer to prayer said the very rev archimandrite 
alexis head of the orthodox community at brookwood the community 
has been looking for saintly relics for its church which it 
renamed st edward the martyr 
edward king of wessex ruled for three years and was only 16 or 
17 when he was stabbed to death in dorset southwest england in 
978 edward was canonized and his bones at shaftesbury abbey in 
dorset attracted pilgrims in the middle ages 
the buried bones were found in 1930 but john and geoffrey 
claridge two brothers who had inherited the site couldnt agree 
on what to do with them 
john claridge kept the bones and eventually presented them to 
the russian community while his geoffrey claridge sought to have 
them returned to the abbey site 
i wanted them to be properly enshrined and only the russian 
orthodox church was prepared to do that john claridge said 
in the decision wright awarded unspecified legal costs to john 
claridge and the brookwood russian community 
alexis head of st edwards brotherhood of brookwood said the 
reason for his churchs interest in the bones dates to the 1054 
split of christendom into eastern and western churches the russian 
church claims edward the martyr as one of its own because the king 
died before the split and worshiped according to its original 
doctrines 
