<TEXT>
engineers today lifted a giant oven lid to 
check a mirror that astronomers hope will lead to the next 
generation of super telescopes and the huge piece of cooling glass 
was pronounced just fine 
i dont know how nervous you are but im certainly feeling 
it peter strittmatter director of the university of arizonas 
steward observatory said monday after engineers began spincasting 
glass into what they hope will become a honeycombed 11foot mirror 
the largest ever to be made in that manner 
colleague roger angel is credited with the idea that he and 
other steward astronomers hoped would bear fruit 
the first 24 hours during which the mirror actually is molded 
are the most critical strittmatter said monday he said scientists 
were lifting the lid today to get a view of a redhot product 
strittmatter said today the mirror apparently formed without any 
problems but that engineers and astronomers will have to wait the 
six weeks until they know for certain whether the mirror was 
successfully produced 
so far so good angel said the trick is to get it from 
this temperature about 1470 degrees fahrenheit down to room 
temperature in one piece 
the mirror a prototype for more powerful telescopes than now 
exist is to be sited at the astrophysical research consortium 
arc telescope being built in the sacramento mountains near sun 
spot nm 
arc is a joint project of five universities the university of 
chicago princeton new mexico state university of washington and 
washington state 
the goal is obviously to make much bigger mirrors than we have 
ever been able to make before strittmatter said 
traditional big mirrors have weighed four to five times more 
than the two tons the finished 11foot mirror will be and have 
required as many as two or three years to grind and polish he said 
in addition they are slow to adjust to outside air temperature 
making for blurred images and require large support structures and 
buildings to house them he said 
the new technology offers many advantages angel and 
strittmatter said combined with a new technique for polishing the 
glass blank with a more deeply curved surface the mirror being 
cast and those to follow will have short focal lengths resulting in 
great cost savings through smaller buildings for the telescopes 
they added 
domed telescopes thus could become a thing of the past said 
donald york of the university of chicago 
strittmatter said the advances have spurred renewed worldwide 
interest in astronomical research with several new major 
telescopes planned including a binocularlike telescope with twin 
26foot mirrors called the columbus project that would be the 
worlds most powerful telescope collaborators include italian 
astronomers the universities of arizona and chicago and ohio state 
university 
mirrors of 26 feet in diameter are considered the current limit 
given atmospheric distortion strittmatter said the honeycombed 
understructure which makes for lightweight yet rigid construction 
helps minimize the distortion he said 
thermal temperatures of the mirror can be controlled much more 
effectively than in conventional telescope mirrors he said 
in the steward mirror lab beneath the stands of the 
universitys football stadium the 19foot furnace began spinning 
about 8 times a minute once its temperature reached 705 degrees 
celsius or about 1300 degrees fahrenheit the furnace began 
heating late saturday 
lab workers cast a 4foot mirror in november with the same 
spinning furnace 
