<TEXT>
the bronze cowboy sculpture the rattlesnake 
by famed western artist frederic remington stopped museum visitor 
cy baumgartner in his tracks the cowboys tiny spurs were on 
upside down 
theres no way a cowboy would wear his spurs pointing up like 
that said baumgartner a former rodeo cowboy who now drives a 
beer truck and raises quarter horses it would be totally out of 
character 
baumgartner who was touring the remington exhibit sunday at the 
st louis art museum apparently was the first to notice the error 
i saw it immediately he said i just think its funny 
that nobody noticed it before now 
after baumgartner pointed out the problem museum workers 
checked other bronzes on display 
they found that all the spurs on the four horsemen in a casting 
of coming through the rye were also upside down 
peter h hassrick one of the curators of the exhibit said he 
has occasionally noticed similar problems with remington works in 
private collections he said he hadnt noticed the problem in the 
st louis exhibit 
but that doesnt necessarily mean that remington the famed 
sculptor and painter of western themes who lived from 1861 to 1909 
made the error 
the spurs on the bronzes and other small pieces were cast 
separately from the main work and as a result it was sometimes 
left to a foundry worker with little knowledge of a cowboys gear 
to attach the spurs to the boots 
on other occasions hassrick said the spurs may have been 
damaged and replacement spurs attached turned the wrong way 
its just a silly little thing but im sure remington wold 
have liked to have seen them the right way hassrick said 
if they were on one of our bronzes wed turn them around 
said hassrick director of the buffalo bill historical center in 
cody wyo and an authority on remington 
neither of the works in question however is owned by the 
museum the rattlesnake casting is from a private collection 
and the casting of coming through the rye is on loan from 
princeton university 
