<TEXT>
the reagan administration urged the supreme 
court on tuesday to scrap a federal law used to prosecute several 
former white house aides and to investigate attorney general edwin 
meese iii 
the law gives too much power to people totally untethered to 
any politically responsible person argued solicitor general 
charles fried the justice departments top courtroom lawyer 
disputed provisions in the ethics in government act of 1978 
allow independent counsels formerly called special prosecutors to 
investigate alleged misconduct by key executivebranch officials 
fried said such investigations should be conducted only by 
officials answerable to the president 
independent counsel alexia morrison defending the law said 
congress wanted to preclude the appearance or the reality of a 
conflict of interest arising from an administration investigating 
itself 
the high courts decision expected by july could help define 
the nations political life in future years 
the decision also could affect the criminal convictions of 
former white house aides michael k deaver and lyn nofziger and the 
irancontra affair prosecutions of exwhite house aides john m 
poindexter and oliver north 
ms morrison is investigating allegations that theodore b 
olson a former assistant attorney general lied to congress in 
1983 during a dispute over the environmental protection agencys 
cleanup program for toxic waste sites 
a federal appeals court ruled the independent counsel law is an 
unconstitutional encroachment on the presidents power to enforce 
criminal laws 
fried urged the justices to uphold the appeals court ruling 
saying the law strips the president of a purely executive 
function criminal prosecution 
he said the law also wrongly absolves congress of its 
weightiest and most painful duty serving as a watchdog for 
abuses of executive power fried said the proper remedy for such 
misconduct is impeachment by congress 
olsons lawyer thomas s martin added that the law radically 
alters the structure of how we are governed 
joining ms morrison in defending the law during a 90minute 
argument session was michael davidson the senates chief lawyer 
davidson fielded questions from several justices who voiced 
concern about the laws empowering a special court rather than the 
president or his subordinates to appoint special prosecutors he 
said such appointment power is a minor aspect of the law 
chief justice william h rehnquist seemed less than convinced 
you cannot assign to one branch certain functions that inherently 
belong to the other he said 
but rehnquist also asked martin olsons lawyer why the 
specialprosecutor provision was dissimilar from congress routinely 
placing limits on a presidents power to remove one of his 
executivebranch appointees 
justice thurgood marshall asked martin shouldnt a prosecutor 
be independent whats wrong with it 
the case is being decided by eight justices because justice 
anthony m kennedy has disqualified himself for unexplained reasons 
his absence creates the possibility of a 44 tie which would 
have the effect of automatically upholding the appeals court 
decision invalidating the law 
asked by reporters whether that possibility concerned her ms 
morrison would not comment saying only i will anxiously await 
the courts ruling 
martin said he did not expect an evenly divided court i think 
a consensus will emerge and i dont expect a 44 split he said 
deaver was convicted of perjury earlier this year for lying to a 
grand jury and a house subcommittee that investigated his lobbying 
activities 
poindexter north and two others were indicted in special 
prosecutor lawrence walshs investigation of the irancontra affair 
independent counsel james c mckay who successfully prosecuted 
nofziger for illegal lobbying also is investigating meese in 
connection with possible financial conflicts of interest 
