scores of workers toiled tuesday to 
rescue waterfowl from a 21000gallon oil spill that officials say 
could leave a major wildlife area damaged for years and cost at 
least 1 million to clean 
now were looking at a dead marsh said neal welsh an 
officer of the audubon society dont get your hopes up for the 
next few decades 
the oil caused the greatest damage to a marsh area in suisun 
bay although a lighter slick extended about 10 miles west through 
the carquinez strait into san pablo bay 
the marsh area 35 to 40 miles northeast of san francisco is 
the most prized wetland of northern california and a major stopover 
along the migratory bird route that extends virtually the length of 
california 
directed by a coast guard helicopter six oil skimmers were 
deployed to the worst oil slicks and vacuum pumps worked day and 
night to suck oil out of the marshes 
the unrefined crude oil leaked from a storage tank saturday at 
shell oil cos martinez refinery the company has acknowledged 
responsibility for the spill 
shells tab for cleanup costs could exceed 1 million said 
larry kolb the water qaulity control boards regional assistant 
executive in addition the company also is likely to face 
penalties and other costs including damage to bottoms of numerous 
pleasure boats he said 
under state law shell could face 210000 in fines 10 a 
gallon and more if the state attorney generals office files a 
successful lawsuit 
the cleanup could continue for days to weeks said kolb 
the damage may be there for years 
state department of fish and game official brian hunter said 
about 200 soiled but living birds have been collected for 
treatment and some 75 birds have been found dead biologists said 
the spill also threatened nests 
the marshes are home to dozens of species of birds including 
egrets avocets grebes sandpipers ducks herons teals and the 
endangered clapper rail bird as well as salt marsh harvest mice 
tortoises muskrats and otters 
