<TEXT>
a senate committee on tuesday approved a 
measure sought by the small aircraft industry that would place 
limits on accident liability 
the measure which was approved by the senate commerce committee 
on a voice vote would establish a series of federal standards for 
determining liability in an accident involving aircraft seating 
less than 20 people and that are not flying scheduled passenger 
routes 
the measure would replace what industry officials and private 
plane owners complain is a hodgepodge of conflicting state laws 
manufacturers argue that their insurance costs have multiplied 
by 500 percent since 1981 as a result of that increase and rising 
court judgments the number of private planes produced in this 
country has declined from a record 17000 in 1979 to 1085 last 
year the industry says 
the bill would place no limit on the amount of money a victim 
could recover in damages but in perhaps its most controversial 
provision it would prohibit accident victims from obtaining 
damages in most cases in which the aircraft was more than 20 years 
old 
consumer groups and trial lawyers have opposed the legislation 
contending it would make it too difficult for victims to collect 
damages and thus eliminate an incentive that manufacturers have to 
make the aircraft safe 
the house aviation subcommittee approved a similar bill march 3 
that would limit manufacturers liability to aircraft 12 years old 
or less but the measure faces bleak prospects in that chamber 
because three full committees public works energy and commerce 
and judiciary must complete work on the legislation before it 
reaches the house floor 
the senate panel sent the bill to the full chamber with sen 
bob packwood objecting the oregon republican complained that the 
measure would make it too difficult for passengers aboard aircraft 
involved in accidents to prove the plane was defective 
the measure is sponsored by sen nancy kassebaum rkan whose 
state is home to cessna aircraft co the beech aircraft corp and 
other private plane builders 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

