a defense lawyer for irancontra defendant 
albert hakim accused prosecutors tuesday of violating a court order 
by trying to limit his clients access to classified documents 
compiled in the case 
the procedures proposed by independent counsel lawrence e walsh 
to limit hakims right to see certain highly sensitive government 
documents directly contravene us district judge gerhard a 
gesells order defense lawyer n richard janis charged in court 
papers 
janis said walshs proposal also would limit access of retired 
air force maj gen richard v secord hakims former business 
partner who also is charged with participating in the illegal 
conspiracy to divert usiran armssale profits to the nicaraguan 
contra rebels 
the two brokered the arms sales through a series of swissbased 
companies which also funneled money to the contras 
under the proposal by walshs office all classified documents 
turned over to the defense would be made available to lawyers for 
hakim and secord as well as counsel for the other two defendants 
marine lt col oliver l north and former national security 
adviser john m poindexter 
north a fired national security council aide and poindexter 
also would be allowed to review all documents furnished to the 
lawyers according to a proposal outlined in a letter sent by 
walshs office this week to defense counsel 
before they left the white house staff in november 1986 both 
north and poindexter had security clearances and access to the 
nations most wellkept secrets and presumably saw or generated 
much of the material collected by walshs investigators 
but walshs proposal said hakim and secord would not get 
automatic access to particularly sensitive information 
this material includes documents whose disclosure would 
jeopardize the lives of hostages in the middle east or compromise 
us intelligence methods particularly sensitive military 
operations and extremely sensitive foreign policy 
initiatives according to the letter 
hakim a native of iran who has us citizenship has never had 
access to government documents secord who once held sensitive 
positions in the pentagon held a number of security clearances 
before his air force retirement 
gesell ordered walsh on april 15 to allow the defense to review 
some 300000 pages of classified material to determine if it would 
help their case an interagency task force is checking the material 
before it is turned over to the defendants to see what highly 
sensitive information is included 
the sensitive documents covered by walshs proposal comprise 
between 5 percent and 10 percent of the material reviewed so far 
defense lawyers were told at a recent meeting with prosecutors 
under the proposal that janis contends violates gesells april 
15 order defense lawyers could show hakim and secord certain 
sensitive documents only after obtaining the judges permission 
it would be within the courts discretion to solicit the 
government for its views and to make special arrangements for 
access as the court deems appropriate associate independent 
counsel geoffrey stewart wrote in the letter outlining the proposal 
to defense counsel 
during the hearing janis told gesell that hakim has no less a 
need than the other defendants to review the documents 
gesell assured janis that he would not bar defense lawyers from 
telling their clients anything about the case including 
information in classified documents 
in his protective order the judge said the defendants and their 
lawyers could gain access to the documents if they signed 
agreements not to disclose the information 
gesells order warned that unauthorized disclosure could result 
in prosecution and he set stringent conditions for working with the 
documents in a special secure area being constructed by the justice 
department 
janis said the proposed procedures directly contravene the 
courts protective order which places only limited conditions on 
access to classified information all of which were met by mr 
hakim and his counsel 
both judicial precedent and the pronouncements of this court 
make it clear that the government must now give mr hakim access to 
the information in its possession or face dismissal of the 
indictment against mr hakim janis said 
under the classified information procedures act classified 
documents deemed relevant to the case could only be introduce as 
evidence by either side if they are declassified by the government 
at the april 12 hearing gesell warned that he would be forced 
to dismiss the case if walsh were unable to get relevant documents 
declassified the classification system must be adjusted to the 
needs of the case or the case will collapse gesell said 
