<TEXT>
every day since the stock market crash a 
halfyear ago an economic crisis of one sort or another has been 
forecast in trade credit stocks bonds car sales and more 
oddly and offering a flash of insight about our times none of 
the crises has arrived they fade quietly no apologies from 
their creators and are replaced by vitally fresh hairraisers 
are mortgage rates headed higher will the federal reserve clamp 
down on the money supply can the dollar be saved 
economically speaking the six months since the great stock 
market crash have been unusually calm the economy has neither 
boomed nor busted the jobless rate has trended lower securites 
have been fairly stable 
it has not been that way in the forecasts had they been right 
securities would be deeply depressed unemployment would have 
soared home mortgages would have been unattainable plants and 
factories would be shutting down 
in short the economy as forecast would be in ruins 
while forecasters suggest it is a miracle their worst estimates 
havent come true it is equally amazing to others that some 
forecasters wont give up in almost every economic forecast there 
remains a sense of punishment due good economic news is seldom 
accepted for what it is instead it provokes forecasts of worse to 
come poor economic news is almost welcomed 
the contrast between forecast and performance is especially 
obvious in the stock market where it has become axiomatic that a 
pervading bearishness in the forecasts indicates of all things a 
higher market to come 
whatever the reasons the persistent sense of fear in the 
forecasts has created the impression that the past six months have 
been ones of turmoil whereas they have been closer to tranquillity 
why then do the fears linger 
a sense of guilt perhaps if the stock market crashed why 
shouldnt a recession follow recessions almost always follow so 
why not now 
a recognition that deep and largely unresolved problems remain 
the trade and budget deficits third world loans a high level of 
credit at every level of the economy the threat of trade wars the 
volatility of markets 
but that doesnt fully explain why the good news is discounted 
the economy for example has been neither strong nor weak and 
either one could cause trouble inflation in one instance 
recession in the other jobs are being created inflation remains 
in check interest rates though edging higher havent been 
jumping around as they once did exports are improving 
eventually there will be a recession because if there is one 
clearly demonstrable trait of economies is that they run in cycles 
sooner or later expansions get out of hand inflation begins 
recession ensues 
while recession is viewed as an event to avoid it can be argued 
that it is necessary for clearing the way for the next expansion 
but to view it that way might be more than the human mind can 
accept 
no less acceptable however than the reign of terror in the 
forecasts of things to come that destroy the calm of the present 
</TEXT>
