<TEXT>
the sound can still be heard in the city 
four or five voices working on a street corner in a resonant 
subway tunnel maybe up on the roof 
doowop crested 25 or 30 years ago with hits such as earth 
angel under the boardwalk and philadelphias own silhouettes 
singing get a job but its never gone away 
in the early 60s this music was disappearing as a trend but 
for the past four or five years its coming back as an underground 
situation said stan weaver tenor with the zip codes 
the hopping and bobbing doowop sound now turns up in 
commercials for mcdonalds kentucky fried chicken and levis blue 
jeans but philadelphias street corners can still attract some 
harmony on a warm evening with a group of guys with nothing but a 
pitch pipe to get started on the right key 
doowop was city music new york philadelphia los angeles 
and thats where it survives 
in philadelphia charlie horners rhythm and blues show on 
wxpnfm keeps the flame alive about 30 singers who couldnt 
afford instruments as teenagers and dont want them now were in 
the studio recently to help horner celebrate his 13th year on the 
air 
horner travels 75 miles from his albumpacked home in south 
bound brook nj to west philadelphia to spin the sides every 
saturday afternoon 
its like having a a second job but a good portion of my 
paycheck goes into records said horner a chemist 
with tens of thousands of records stacked on the floor couch 
and tables of his new jersey apartment horner has plenty of tunes 
from which to choose 
and with a man who spends every spare moment and all his spare 
change on this music dont call them oldies or nostalgia theyre 
terms that make horner wince to him these songs arent locked in 
the past or symbols of a lost era 
the type of music we play on the air is mostly from the 50s 
but thats just an accident of time he said 
horner started in college as a deejay on drexel universitys 
studentrun radio station then moved on to wxpn 
he hasnt found any reason to leave a microphone that puts him 
at the center of doowop singers and fans in philadelphia 
during his radio show horner fields telephone calls from 
singers who recorded the 30 or 35yearold records he plays 
occassionaly he finds himself as the middleman in a reunion 
the keystoners credit horner with bringing the group back together 
after 25 years of estrangement five years ago they sang in public 
for the first time since 1958 and are back recording hoping to 
relive the success of their regional hit magic kiss 
most singers though realize doowop stands little chance of 
ever being more than a hobby for them 
you have to love to sing because youre not going to get rich 
off it horner said 
were looking forward to something very serious said harold 
shipman baritone with choice a group that traveled from northern 
new jersey to sing live on horners show during the anniversary 
special 
while doowop bears the imprint of church choirs and of mellow 
quartets such as the mills brothers horton says the specific 
doowop sound can be traced to sonny til and the orioles whose 
1948 hit its too soon to know inspired black teenagers to 
sing on the street corners horner said 
he was to blacks what frank sinatra was to whites at the 
time horner said 
tils group was among the first to use a wordless falsetto with 
other parts singing nonsensical syllables to round out the chord 
doowop legend has it that the ravens bass singer jimmy ricks 
mistakenly started singing his part a few notes early one night 
drawing a gleeful and raucous response from the crowd at the apollo 
theater in harlem the doowop bass lead was born with ricks 
singing lead the group scored a hit with old man river 
the orioles 1949 hit dont tell me so reached no 1 on 
the rhythm and blues charts while crying in the chapel hit no 
11 on the pop charts making it one of the first rampb songs to cross 
over into the white market 
for black kids it was something they heard all their lives 
it was white america that suddenly turned on to it in the 
mid50s horner said 
horner isnt sure when it happened but at some point he turned 
from a fan to a historian of vocal harmony 
with karen caplan he is working on a book about the delta 
rhythm boys whose style was more an extension of jazz than rhythm 
and blues the delta rhythm boys went to finland in 1960 when their 
popularity in this country waned 
the sad thing is a lot of forms of american music while they 
have diehard fans need mass appeal its unfortunate a lot of 
black musicians have to go to europe he said 
lee gains of the delta rhythm boys probably one of the best 
bass singers in the history of the planet in horners estimation 
died july 15 1987 seven days later while singing a spiritual at 
the funeral hugh bryant suffered a fatal heart attack 
with two members of the group dead horner is more determined to 
chronicle the music and its influences 
people may not appreciate it the music now but might in 
2050 and wont know anything about it im trying to preserve the 
history of this music before its lost horner said 
</TEXT>
