<DOCNO> AP880426-0259 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
lurking among the canvases of langorous 
polynesian nudes in the national gallery of arts new exhibition of 
the works of paul gauguin is a curious surprise a wood carving 
that tells much about the enigmatic french artist 
it is an elaborate door frame that gaugin sculpted from redwood 
to decorate the entrance to the house of pleasure his 
primitive hut on the remote marquesan island of hivaoa in the south 
seas where he spent the last three years of his life 
carved on both sides of the base amid a tangle of nude figures 
tropical fruits animals and leafy garlands are the two simple 
commandments that seemed to frame gauguins own scandalous life 
inscribed in french one reads be amorous and you will be 
happy the other is be mysterious 
they were obeyed with joyous abandon by gauguin who renounced 
his family and his prosperous career as a paris stockbroker to 
pursue an artistic vision that led him to denmark brittany 
panama martinique tahiti and finally the marquesas islands 
where he died in 1903 at the age of 55 
the art of gauguin as the postimpressionist master and the 
legend of gauguin as the freespirited libertine are inseparable in 
the national gallerys latest blockbuster the first major 
exhibition of gauguins works in nearly 30 years and the most 
comprehensive ever held 
the show which took five years to assemble opened sunday for a 
threemonth engagement before traveling to the art institute of 
chicago where it will be on view from sept 17 through dec 11 
and the grand palais in paris jan 10 through april 20 next year 
admission at the national gallery is free but passes are 
required in anticipation of heavy crowds the exhibition is 
underwritten by american telephone amp telegraph co in the united 
states and by olivetti in paris 
the curators focused on the depth and range of gauguins art 
rather than the romantic mythology surrounding his remarkable 
personal life gauguins abstract images flattened sense of space 
and daring use of color which he called a profound mysterious 
language a language of the dream clearly inspired picasso 
matisse and other 20th century modernists 
youll find gauguin to be a fabulous and satisfying artist and 
an enigmatic one said richard brettell director of the dallas 
museum of art and one of the principal curators of the exhibition 
the 243 objects in the show include paintings sculpture 
ceramics prints and drawings on loan from museums and private 
collections around the world from japan australia and south 
america to europe the middle east and the soviet union 
brettell said soviet authorities were wonderfully 
cooperative in lending 11 paintings from their countrys gauguin 
collection the most important in the world 
many of the drawing and pictures including the soviet entries 
from the hermitage museum at leningrad and the pushkin state museum 
of fine arts in moscow have never before been displayed in a major 
exhibition even in the slightly larger gauguin memorial show that 
his friends mounted in paris in 1906 
but brettell said two of gauguins largest and most highly 
prized paintings which the curators wanted desperately for the 
national gallery show will be absent because they are too fragile 
to travel 
both painted in tahiti in 1898 they are rupe rupe gathering 
fruit at the hermitage and where do we come from what are we 
where are we going which remains at the boston museum of fine 
arts 
a personal favorite of gallery director j carter brown is the 
siesta which is owned by american publisher walter h annenberg 
and has not been exhibited publicly for a quartercentury 
brettell and charles f stuckey curator of 20th century art at 
the art institute of chicago flew to tahiti to select two wood 
carvings by gauguin from a small museum bearing his name one was a 
bowl for eating poi a fruit paste the other was the missing 
section of the decorative door frame which is housed in the museum 
dorsay in paris 
from tahiti the two curators chartered a twoengine 
propellerdriven plane for a harrowing sevenhour flight through 
tropical storms at low altitudes across more than 900 miles of the 
south pacific to the marquesas bretell calls them the most 
remote islands on earth the end of civilization in the tropics 
there they found gauguins burial site on the outskirts of a 
village on hivaoa the artists final refuge from the civilizing 
influence of french bureaucrats and missionaries who had occupied 
his beloved tahiti 
gauguin it seems had carefully cultivated his popular image 
even to the grave the headstone he sculpted for himself was his 
poetic image of an ancient polynesian spirit called oviri 
which means savage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

