<DOCNO> AP880426-0301 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the colon free zone normally one 
of the worlds busiest trading centers is unusually quiet these 
days 
huge container trucks stand unused in the zones narrow streets 
empty cardboard boxes are piled on the sidewalks and workers sit 
idle waiting for something to do 
panamas political and economic crisis has dealt a severe blow 
to the colon free zone considered the second largest in the world 
after hong kong 
since the deepening of the nations woes in late february trade 
has slowed dramatically small firms have shut their doors and 
employees have been placed on unpaid leave 
the situation couldnt be worse said francisco anderson 
president of the colon free zone users association which 
represents businesses here 
jaime v mizrachi manager of mizratex said weve never seen 
a situation like this ever 
and a truck driver who refused to give his name for fear of 
reprisals said theres nothing to do 
hes had little work in nearly two months he said there are 
few buyers purchasing goods that need to be hauled outside the 
zone the total value of trade in the center was 2054 million in 
march a 361 percent drop from march 1987 according to the zones 
administrative office 
broken down the figures show that the value of goods imported 
to the zone plunged 549 percent last month exports were off 174 
percent 
anderson expects an even worse trade picture this month he 
projects a decline of 50 percent or more in the total value of 
commerce 
the current situation puts in imminent danger the existence of 
the firms and the 8000 permanent jobs of panamanians who work in 
the zone the users association said recently 
the contraction comes after businesses rang up 433 billion in 
trade in all of last year the highest since the 94acre center was 
created in 1948 
before the crisis virtually paralyzed the nations economy 
government officials had been projecting another banner year in 
1988 latin american countries the zones target group have 
shaken off some of their economic woes and been more flush with 
cash in recent years 
located in the city of colon at the caribbean entrance to the 
panama canal the free zone acts as a channel for trade 
such consumer goods as televisions jewelry cosmetics 
clothing liquor and pharmaceuticals flow into the zone from japan 
the united states taiwan hong kong britain switzerland and 
elsewhere 
once in the zone the products are stored repackaged taken 
apart or put together and sent on to buyers mostly in latin america 
if bound for other countries goods are free of duties 
assessments and fees profits are taxed at low rates 
more than 700 companies have set up shop in the zone and 
hundreds more are represented here 
but with the nations latest troubles businessmen say some 
small firms have already packed up and left if you take a walk 
you can see a lot of places that say for rent or for sale 
said anderson two months ago you couldnt get 50 meters of 
space in here to rent out 
he is worried that those that go are not going to come back 
and its going to be very difficult to get new business 
the key problem for the zone was the governments march 3 
closure of the nations international banking center the banks 
suffered a cash squeeze aggravated by the freezing of official 
panamanian deposits in us banks the shortage prevented the 
government from providing panamas dozen locally owned and operated 
banks with enough money to cover a run on deposits that began feb 
26 when military strongman gen manuel antonio noriega ousted 
the president eric arturo delvalle 
since then the reagan administration has imposed sweeping 
sanctions on panama in an effort to force the removal of noriega 
who is under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking 
charges 
the closing of the banks has been the most damaging single 
effect on the free zone said alfredo l maduro general manager 
of the firm herbert toledano 
the trade center is highly dependent on credit money is lent to 
firms in the zone to buy imports and to latin american buyers who 
then purchase those goods for reexport 
ninetyfive percent of the business in the free zone 
involves banking said anderson we do it through banks we 
dont use cash at all 
the national banking commission the governments bank 
regulatory agency has recently permitted the nations 
approximately 120 banks to resume limited operations 
late monday the commission announced the banks could resume 
with certain restrictions handling letters of credit an 
instrument widely used in the free zone to guarantee payment 
businessmen doubted the step would have much impact on their 
trade because of the restricted service and uncertainty about the 
nations future 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

