<TEXT>
cnw corp and a new york investment firm have 
canceled a planned 578 million leveraged buyout of the 
chicagobased transportation and manufacturing company because of 
legal questions the company announced tuesday 
the investment banking firm gibbons green van amerongen and a 
cnw senior management group had offered 31 a share to acquire the 
company in a deal that cnw spokesman james foote said hinged 
partly on cnws plan to sell some of its local and regional routes 
in wisconsin and michigans upper peninsula 
a number of railroad companies including cnw are involved in 
lawsuits with union workers who contend railroads have an 
obligation to bargain with their employees over the sale of local 
and regional routes foote said 
in february in light of the unresolved legal issues cnw and 
gibbons green extended the closing date for the deal one month to 
may 31 
because of continuing uncertainties concerning labor aspects 
of regional line sales the merger could not be consummated prior 
to the may 31 deadline james r wolfe cnws chairman and chief 
executive stated tuesday 
the board concluded that an extension of that deadline was not 
in the best interests of cnw shareholders wolfe said 
the leveraged buyout deal approved by cnws board on nov 16 
consisted of a package of cash and securities valued at 31 a share 
cnw fell 1 to 2312 in trading tuesday on the new york stock 
exchange 
the deal called for gibbons green to own 575 percent of the 
succeeding companys common stock the senior cnw investment group 
led by wolfe was to hold a 72 percent stake with 353 percent 
held publicly 
cnw owns the chicago and north western transportation co a 
leading freight hauler in the midwest and great plains states 
</TEXT>
